lod.config.client.quickEnableRendering.@: Determines if Distant Horizons Renders LODs.
lod.config.client.qualityPresetSetting.@: Will modify a number of settings to quickly change Distant Horizons' rendering quality.
lod.config.client.threadPresetSetting.@t:
Will modify a number of settings to quickly change how many CPU resources Distant Horizons' is allowed to use. 

Increasing this setting will improve Distant Generator speed and LOD loading speed, 
but will also increase CPU/memory usage and may introduce stuttering.
lod.config.client.optionsButton.@tooltip: Show the config button to the left of the fov button
lod.config.client.advanced.graphics.qual:
The maximum detail LODs are rendered at.

§6Fastest:§r Chunk
§6Fanciest:§r Block

Distant Horizons' render distance, measured in chunks. 

Note: this is a best effort number. 
The render distance may be above or below this number 
depending on your other graphic settings.

How well LODs represent overhangs, caves, cliffsides, etc.

Higher options will increase memory and GPU usage.

How quickly LODs drop off in quality.

Larger numbers will improve how distant terrain looks
but will increase memory and GPU usage.

How far apart drops in quality are.

Higher settings will increase the distance between drops
but will increase memory and GPU usage.

This is the same as vanilla Biome Blending settings for LOD area. 

Note that anything other than '0' will greatly effect Lod building time
and increase triangle count. The cost on chunk generation speed is also 
quite large if set to too high.

'0' equals to Vanilla Biome Blending of '1x1', 
'1' equals to Vanilla Biome Blending of '3x3', 
'2' equals to Vanilla Biome Blending of '5x5'...
The distance(s) Fog will be rendered on the LODs.
When fog will be rendered on the LODs.
The color of the fog on LODs.

§6True:§r disables Minecraft's fog on vanilla chunks.
§6False:§r Minecraft renders fog like normal.

May cause issues with other mods that edit fog.
Disable if vanilla chunks are completely covered in fog.

Where should the far fog start? 

  '0.0': Fog start at player's position.
  '1.0': The fog-start's circle fit just in the lod render distance square.
'1.414': The lod render distance square fit just in the fog-start's circle.

Where should the far fog end? 

  '0.0': Fog end at player's position.
  '1.0': The fog-end's circle fit just in the lod render distance square.
'1.414': The lod render distance square fit just in the fog-end's circle.

What is the minimum fog thickness? 

  '0.0': No fog at all.
  '1.0': Fully fog color.

What is the maximum fog thickness? 

  '0.0': No fog at all.
  '1.0': Fully fog color.

How should the fog thickness should be calculated? 

LINEAR: Linear based on distance (will ignore 'density')
EXPONENTIAL: 1/(e^(distance*density)) 
EXPONENTIAL_SQUARED: 1/(e^((distance*density)^2)

How the height should effect the fog thickness combined with the normal function? 

BASIC: No special height fog effect. Fog is calculated based on camera distance 
IGNORE_HEIGHT: Ignore height completely. Fog is calculated based on horizontal distance 
ADDITION: heightFog + farFog 
MAX: max(heightFog, farFog) 
MULTIPLY: heightFog * farFog 
INVERSE_MULTIPLY: 1 - (1-heightFog) * (1-farFog) 
LIMITED_ADDITION: farFog + max(farFog, heightFog) 
MULTIPLY_ADDITION: farFog + farFog * heightFog 
INVERSE_MULTIPLY_ADDITION: farFog + 1 - (1-heightFog) * (1-farFog) 
AVERAGE: farFog*0.5 + heightFog*0.5 

Note that for 'BASIC' mode and 'IGNORE_HEIGHT' mode, fog settings for height fog has no effect.

Where should the height fog be located? 

ABOVE_CAMERA: Height fog starts from camera to the sky 
BELOW_CAMERA: Height fog starts from camera to the void 
ABOVE_AND_BELOW_CAMERA: Height fog starts from camera to both the sky and the void 
ABOVE_SET_HEIGHT: Height fog starts from a set height to the sky 
BELOW_SET_HEIGHT: Height fog starts from a set height to the void 
ABOVE_AND_BELOW_SET_HEIGHT: Height fog starts from a set height to both the sky and the void
If the height fog is calculated around a set height, what is that height position?

How far the start of height fog should offset? 

  '0.0': Fog start with no offset.
  '1.0': Fog start with offset of the entire world's height. (Include depth)

How far the end of height fog should offset? 

  '0.0': Fog end with no offset.
  '1.0': Fog end with offset of the entire world's height. (Include depth)

What is the minimum fog thickness? 

  '0.0': No fog at all.
  '1.0': Fully fog color.

What is the maximum fog thickness? 

  '0.0': No fog at all.
  '1.0': Fully fog color.

How should the height fog thickness should be calculated? 

LINEAR: Linear based on height (will ignore 'density')
EXPONENTIAL: 1/(e^(height*density)) 
EXPONENTIAL_SQUARED: 1/(e^((height*density)^2)
What is the height fog's density?
lod.config.client.advanced.graphics.nois: If enabled a noise texture will be applied to LODs to simulate textures.
Determines how intense the noise texture is.

How far should the noise texture render before it fades away? 

0.0 - the noise texture will render the entire LOD render distance. 
3.0 - the noise texture will fade away at 1/3 of the LOD render distance.
lod.config.client.advanced.graphics.adva:
Enabling this will prevent some overdraw issues,
but may cause nearby LODs to render incorrectly, especially when near fancy leaves or non-full blocks.
Less noticeable with a longer vanilla render distance.

How bright LOD colors are.

0 = black 
1 = normal 
2 = near white

How saturated LOD colors are.

0 = black and white 
1 = normal 
2 = vibrant

If enabled caves will be culled 

Additional Info: Currently this cull all faces 
 with skylight value of 0 under the cave culling height in dimensions that 
 do not have a ceiling.
At what Y value should cave culling start?
A value of 1 is equivalent to the curvature of Earth in real life.

Sets vanilla's lod bias value
Please press F3+T to reload the texture packs and apply this effect
lod.config.client.advanced.worldGenerato:
§6True:§r in single player LODs will be generated outside the vanilla render distance.
Note: this can use a large amount of CPU.

§6False:§r LODs will only generate within the vanilla render distance.

How complicated the generation should be when generating LODs outside the vanilla render distance.

§6§6Fastest:§r Biome only
§6Best Quality:§r Features (suggested)

§6Minecraft:§r use Minecraft's lighting engine, gives accurate lighting.
§6Distant Horizons:§r estimates lighting, shadows won't be as smooth, but is more stable.

If the LODs appear black, set this to §6Distant Horizons§r.
The priority for chunks being generated around the player.
Defines the types of blocks to ignore when generating LODs.

§4Note: makes snow, carpet, and trapdoors look really bad§r
Should the blocks underneath avoided blocks gain the color of the avoided block?
§6True:§r a red flower on grass will tint the grass below it red
§6False:§r skipped blocks will not change color of surface below them

lod.config.client.multiplayer.multiDimen:
When matching worlds of the same dimension type the
tested chunk(s) must be at least this percent the same
in order to be considered the same world.

Note: If you use portals to enter a dimension at two
different locations this system may think it is two different worlds.

§61.0:§r the chunks must be identical.
§60.5:§r the chunks must be half the same.
§60.0:§r disables multi-dimension support
     only one world will be used per dimension.
lod.config.client.advanced.threading.num:
How many threads should be used when generating LODs 
 outside the normal render distance? 

If it this is less than 1, it will be treated as a percentage 
of time a single thread can run before going idle. 

If you experience stuttering when generating distant LODs, 
decrease  this number. If you want to increase LOD 
generation speed, increase this number. 

This and the number of buffer builder threads are independent, 
if they add up to more threads than your CPU has cores 
that is ok.

The number of threads used when building geometry data.
Can only be between 1 and your CPU's processor count.

The number of threads used when building vertex buffers
(The things sent to your GPU to draw the LODs).
Can only be between 1 and your CPU's processor count.

The number of threads used when converting ID data to render-able data.
(This generally happens when generating new terrain or changing graphics settings).
Can only be between 1 and your CPU's processor count.

lod.config.client.advanced.buffers.gpuUp:
The method for uploading geometry to the GPU.

If you experience stuttering while your CPU and GPU usage is low, try changing this setting.
Note: if you are in a world you may have to leaving and rejoin to see the full effect.

How long should a buffer wait per Megabyte of data uploaded?
May be increased if there is frame stuttering.
